### Milestone 5 — Adaptive entropy model (ongoing refinement)
Version 4 stream: per-ratio hybrid mode. Justified by M3/M4 benchmark data.
Not a hard deliverable — iterated as findings accumulate.

Design:
  The v3 EntropyQuantized mode quantizes ALL ClassNormal ratios to N bits, which
  is lossy regardless of whether the data actually needs that precision. The v4
  hybrid avoids unnecessary loss:

  For each ClassNormal ratio, compute the quantization error at PrecisionBits.
  - If error < tolerance (ε): store as uint16 quantized symbol (compact, lossy
    only by at most ε — the data "doesn't care" at this precision)
  - If error ≥ tolerance (ε): emit new class ClassNormalExact and store the full
    float64 (no information loss for this ratio)

  At ε=0: degenerates to fully lossless (all ratios take the exact path).
  At ε=∞: degenerates to v3 EntropyQuantized (all ratios take the quantized path).
  At practical ε: smooth data (Sensor, NearConstant) compresses near v3 ratios
  with near-zero data loss; high-entropy data (Financial) falls back to exact
  storage on the ratios that resist quantization — no false compression.

  This is NOT the same as the adaptive precision-selection idea (auto-selecting
  PrecisionBits via AnalyzePrecision). That is a simpler pre-encode pass feeding
  into v3. The v4 hybrid is a per-ratio decision at encode time.

