## Future enhancements (not scheduled)

Effort key: S = hours, M = 1–3 days, L = 1–2 weeks, XL = milestone-sized

---

### Nice to have — clear value, no pre-work required

### SIMD / intrinsics for QuantizeRatio hot loop  [effort: M]
Go's compiler handles the inner loop reasonably today. Hand-written SIMD
(via assembly or cgo) could lift throughput 2–4× on x86-64/ARM. Requires
profiling to confirm it is actually the bottleneck before investing.

### Streaming encode (io.Reader input)  [effort: M]
Replace the slice-based Encode API with a streaming encoder that does not
require the full array in memory — useful for very large files or
pipe-based workflows. API-breaking change; requires a new public interface.
Candidate post-M11 once the 1D design is stable.

### Parallel encode (goroutines per reanchor segment)  [effort: M]
Each reanchor segment is fully independent — embarrassingly parallel.
A worker-pool encoder could saturate multiple cores with no correctness
risk. With adaptive reanchoring, segment boundaries are data-driven so a
two-pass approach is needed (pass 1: identify boundaries; pass 2: encode
segments in parallel). Decode parallelism requires a segment offset table
in the stream header — new stream version. Worth doing after M11.

### 2D / multi-dimensional extension  [effort: XL]
Accept a 2D float64 array; encode each row as a ratio stream; add
cross-row prediction for spatially correlated columns. Relevant for sensor
matrices, time-series databases, and neural weight tensors. Changes the
fundamental API contract. Revisit after the white paper establishes and
validates the 1D design. Candidate for a separate package or v2 module.

---

### Benchmark-gated — only proceed if a benchmark first shows measurable gain

### 24-bit payload tier  [effort: M]
A 24-bit tier would cover sig figs 5–7 at 3 bytes instead of 4, saving
25% for that precision range. Requires manual bit packing, a new class
symbol, new 8-symbol rANS alphabet, and a new stream version byte —
M7-scale work. Current harness shows Q-6sf and Q-9sf produce identical
file sizes (both u32), so the u32 tier is not demonstrably over-used.
Gate on: harness showing a materially different byte count between
17-bit and 30-bit precision on a real dataset.

### Delta coding of quantized index stream  [effort: L]
Before rANS, encode the delta between adjacent class symbols rather than
the raw symbols. For smooth data Δ≈0 dominates, giving a more skewed
distribution and higher rANS compression. Zero benefit for volatile/random
data. Requires a new stream version.
Gate on: prototype delta transform showing ≥5% ratio improvement on
at least two dataset classes in the existing harness.

### Context-adaptive rANS  [effort: L]
Maintain per-context frequency tables (keyed on previous class symbol)
instead of one global table. Each per-context distribution has lower
entropy than the global one. Header grows by one table per context.
Meaningful gain only when class transitions are structured.
Gate on: entropy analysis showing per-context entropy materially lower
than global entropy on target datasets.

### v6 — Predictive-residual lossless stream  [effort: L]
A predictor (last ratio or linear extrapolation) + entropy-coded residual
could achieve genuinely lossless compression better than v2's ~1.0 ratio.
Key risk: ratios are already a first-difference transform on values; a
second differencing layer may yield little in practice.
Gate on: prototype residual coder showing lossless ratio < 0.90 on
Smooth/Sensor dataset (current lossless is ~1.0007 — near-zero gain).
